{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_finch_ver01/data/sn84020107/00517014874/1908022701/0254.xml":{"full_text":"vnTTTMR 25. NUMBER 35.\nBEATRICE, NEBRASKA, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 27, 1908.\nEVENING EDITION. I\nDemocrats of County Meet and\nSelect' Delegates to the\nState Convention.\nUNANIMOUS FOR BRYAN\nIndorse Jacob Klein, bp., fop District\nDelegate to Denver\u2014Conven\ntion Is barge and En\nthusiastic.\nThe largest democratic convention\nheld in Gage county for some years\nconvened in the district\u2019court room\n/\u2018at the court house this morning at 11\no'clock.\nThe faces of many old democratic\nVhr horses, men who have fought for\ndemocratic principles in good and bad\nweather, were noticed among the del\negates.\nGene Mumford, who crawled over\nthe breastworks in 1896, was con\nspicuous by his'presence, and was\nhonored by being elected secretary.\n.Jim Hutson, who has been a familiar\nfigure at previous conventions, was\nmissing owing to illness. Among\nthose on hand without whom a demo\ncratic county convention would be\nmighty lonesome were Dr. C. P. Fall,\nW. A. Foreman, J. A. Klein, Andrew\nAndersen, Alex 'Andersen, William\nCarrithers, Dr. H. A. Given of Wy\nmore, Richard Whitton of Wymore,\nJ. R. Montgomery of Pickrell and A.\nR. Patton of Blue Springs.\nThe delegates were enthusiastic\nand applauded the name of William\nJennings Bryan whenever opportu-j\nnity afforded. They spoke cheerful\nly of a sweeping democratic victory\nwhich they believe will come next\nfall and will hurl the epemy from the\npie counters.\nThe convention was called to order\nby Chairman F. O. McGirr, who made\nan eloquent speech along democratic\nlines. He said 4hat the present year\ntg a year when democrats could make\neloquent speeches. He liked t\u00b0 see\na big bunch of democrats together.\nIn days gone by the democrats were\ndissatisfied; they differed on princi\nples. This is not so today. The\ndemocratic party is now united and\nfighting together for the re-establish\nment of democracy in the nation. He\nremarked that the republicans it\ntimes past had charged that a panic\nhad never occurred under a republi\ncan administration; that with a high\ntariff and a gold atandard, a, panic\nwas impossible. This fallacy had been\nexploded during Roosevelt\u2019s adminis\ntration. The alleged partnership\nwith Providence had been dissolved.\nMr. McGirr then called for nomi\nnations for temporary chairman.\nGeorge W. Campbell of Wymore,\nwas placed in nomination and elected\nunanimously. Mr. McGirr stated in\nrelinquishing the chair that Mr.\nCampbell needed no introduction to\nthe democrats of G&ge county, as the\nBeatrice Daily and Weekly Express\nf had already attended to that.\nMr. Campbell was given an enthu\nsiastic reception. He thanked the\nconvention for the honor of presiding\nover its deliberations and stated that\ntherq never was a time when it was\nmore of an honor to be a democrat\nthan now. Speeches were neither\nnecessary nor appropriate. The del\negates were on hand for a fixed pur\npose\u2014the election of delegates to the\nstate convention, which convention\nwill select delegates to attend the na\ntional convention and place in nomi\nnation the next president of the Uni\nted States, William Jennings Bryan.\nE. P. Mumford was elected tempo\nrary secretary which caused Mr.\nCampbell to smilingly remark that\n\u25a0he \u201cwas glad to see Gene back\nagain.\u201d\nOn motion the chair appointed\nO. McGlrr, A. R. Patton and H. Lacy\nas a committee on credentials.\nThere being no contests, the com\nmittee recommended the adoption of\nthe lists handed in by the chairman\nof each delegation as the list of del\negates comprising the convention.\nHS On motion a committee of five was\n1 appointed on resolutions. The chair\nnamed T. E. Stewart, Menzo Teity,\nDr. H. A. Given. Dr. C. P. Fall and\nW. A.-Foreman as such committee.\nA committee composed of A. R.\nPatton. Dr. Fall, F. Q. McGlrr, Dr.\nH. A. Given and John Saylor was ap\npointed to select delegates to the\nstate convention to be held at Oma\nha, the list to be ratified by the con\nvention.\nDr. cr P. Fall made a plea for\nmembers of the Bryan volunteers. It\ncosts $10 to join, the money to be\nused in defraying the expenses of the\nconvention. Ten names were secured.\nThe convention then adjourned un\ntil this afternoon at 2 o\u2019clock:\nThe afternoon session did not con\nvene until after 2 o\u2019clock, being de\nlayed to allow the committee on del\negation to the state convention time\nto formulate their report.\nT. E. Stewart, chairman of the res\nolutions committee, submitted the\nfollowing report, which was adopted:\nWt, the democracy of Gage coun\nty, Neb., in regular convention as\nsembled, point with pride to the forty\nyears of democratic rule from Jefter\nson to Jackson, during which time\nno panic occurred. We believe the\npresent financial panic, coming with\nin a period of 16 years since the one\nhanded to us by the former republi\ncan administration, justifies a return\nto democratic principles as taught by\nthose statesmen; and do hereby ex\ntend our sincere sympathy to the\nthousands of unemployed throughout\nthe United States who are now idle\nas a result of the present financial\npanic which was brought about by\nthe stock gamblers of Wall street,\nwho dictate the policies of the repub\nlican party; and as a remedy for ex\nisting evils we advocate the restora\ntion of confidence by a return to a\ndemocratic government, administered\nby representatives of the people,\nelected by the people without the\naid or consent of the stock gamblers\nor trusts, and believing him to be the\ngreatest exponent of human rights,\nin this or any other land, a safe and\nable statesman, possessing the love,\nconfidence and respect of law-abiding\npeople everywhere, we therefore fa\nvor first, last and all the time and\nhereby pledge our united support to\nthat great commoner, our distin\nguished fellow-citizen, William Jen\nnings Bryan, for the presidency of\nthe United States,\nThe following list of delegates and\nalternates was reported by the com\nmittee and endorsed by the conven\ntion:\nDelegates: F. O. McGlrr, T. E.\nStewart, Jacob Klein, jr., G. P. Mar\nvin, Dr. G. L. Roe, C. C. Farlow, Dr.\nJ. I. McGirr, Dr. H. A. Given, George\nCampbell, Julius Neumann, R. J.\nHarris, J. R. Montgomery, F. W.\nMumford, I. T. Merchant, W. A.\nForeman, Thos. Stanoscheck, J. B.\nFulton, T. R. Calland, Wm. Nolan,\nLester Kurtz, A. R. Patton, A. R.\nMorris, Hiram Bear, Menzo Terry,\nJ. A. Wiggins, Alfred Hazlett, C. P.\nFall.\nAlternates: Andrew Anderson, jas.\nBaer, Dr. J. S. McCleery, Earl Mar\nvin, Edward Erb, W. E. McOlrr, O.\nP. Mentgen, H. Lacey, Cbas. Vance,\nD. Delehant, J. B. Montgomery, M.\nD. Baumer, A. D. Graf, Geo. Wilkla\nson'T'J. R. Sayllng, O. P. Fulton, J.\nB. Kaufman, Pat Rawley, Clark Dom\ning, Rr. E. Simmons, John Gerdes,\nJ. C. Wyatt, E. J. Shinn, A. McClar\nren, C. D. Moody, E. P. Mumford, W.\nCarrithers.\nWith the committee reports dis\nposed of Dr. C. P. Fall took the floor\nand made a strong plea for the Bry\nan Volunteers'\nHe was followed by several others\nwho discussed the matter of finances,\nsome urging the cause of the state\ncommittee, others emphasizing the\nimportance of local work and favor\ning devoting the larger part of the\nfunds to home needs. A number of\nspeeches were made, the two ele\nments -gradually. bacmootping- _\nSpeeches wdre made by Dr. Fall,\nChairman Geo. Campbell, Dr. Given,\nJacob Klein, T. E. Stewart, John\nGardes and Chas. Vance. Nearly ev\nery speaker delved into the past and\nbrought out many interesting and\nentertaining features of past cam\npaigns. The mention of W. J. Bry\nan\u2019s name was invariably a signal\nfor a burst of applause.\nJacob Klein for Delegate.\nT. E. Stewart was given the floor\nand made a motion endorsing Jacob\nKlein for district delegate to the\nnational convention at Denver. The\nmotion was passed unanimously.\nDr. Fall then renewed his plea in\nbehalf of the state committee. More\nthan a dozen pledges were received.\nF. O. McGirr urged the importance\nof local clubs to aid in conducting\nthe work of the campaign. G. A.\nWilkinson followed with a motion in\nstructing each township committee\nman to organize such a club in bis\nlocality.\nFollowing the motion endorsing\nhim for delegate Mr. Klein address\ned the convention briefly, thanking\nthem for the honor conferred upon\nhim.\nThe convention was harmonious\nthroughout and enthusiastically com\nmitted to the support of W. J. Bryan\nfor president'.\nMlchael-Krause.\nGeorge Michael of Armour, Neb.,\nand Miss Anna Krause of this city,\nwere united in marriage at the\nChristian parsonage at high noon to\nday, Rev. J. E. Davis officiating. The\nceremony was Witnessed by the im\nmediate relatives and a few friends\not the young couple.\nThe bride has lived in this vicinity\nfor a number of years and is highly\nesteemed by all who know her. The\nj groom is a prosperous young farmer\nliving near Armour.\nMr. and Mrs. Michael left this aftr\nj ernoon over the Burlington for Ar\nmour, where they will make their\nhome. Their many friends join with\nj The Express in wishing the young\ncouple much happiness and prosper\nity.\nCentenary Choir Attention.\nRemember that our rehearsal Fri\nday evening will be held at the par\nsonage, on account of the lecture in\nthe church. Be sure and be present,\nand do not forget that lunch box\nwhich may 'contain anything good' to\neat you may choose to bring. Don\u2019t\nforget. Leader.\n\nA Ring\u2019s Dyspepsia Tablet after\neach meal overcomes indigestion,\ndyspepsia, and sother stomach. Ills.\nTwo days* trial free. Ask our deal\ner. Sold by W. Boswell.\nA BITTER PILL FOR HIM.\n^BIG\nSTICK\nHAVE FENCE IN\nOfficials Believe Gang of Yegg\nmen Are Workingin This\nSection.\nMEMBERS IN BEATRICE\n\nDifficult to Obtain Evidence Against\nGang\u2014H. D. Gerhtrdt Bobbed\nof Seventeen Suits of\nClothing.\ni Sheriff Trude and the police offi\ncials of this and adjoining cities are\nconvinced that there is a gang of\n\u201cyeggmen\u201d working in southeastern\nNebraska and that they have a fence\nIn southern Gage county.\nOf late numerous robberies have\nbeen reported in this section but the\nperpetrators, feave^apt been run to\ncover as yet. The latest robbery Is\nthat of the clothing store of H. D.\nGerhardt at Plymouth. Eighteen\nsuits of clothes have been stolen\nfrom his place of business within the\nlast few days. No -due to the guilty\nparties has been found.\nSheriff Trude asserts that there is\na gang of yeggmen working out of\nWymore; that members of the gang\nalso live in this city and that a fence\nis maintained either in or near Wy\nmore. Recently men who were sell\ning various articles of wearing ap\nparel have been ordered out of the\ncity. The plan of members of this\ngang is to steal goods in one town,\nsend the stolen property to another\ntown and then dispose of them. So\nshrewd are the members of the gang\nthat when captured none of them\nhappen to have any of the stolen\ngoods in their possession.\nAn effort to rid the county of the\nsuspects is soon to be made.\nWymore Neys Notes.\nWymore, Neb., Feb. 26.\u2014Last eve\nning the B. of R. T. and the ladies\u2019\nauxiliary of that order gave their an\nnual ball and it was a great success.\nThe hall was decorated with colored\nlights and paper drapery. Guests\nwere present from all over the divi\nsion. The hall was too crowded ear\nly in the evening to make dancing\nenjoyable. In.an adjoining room a\nbanquet was served by the ladles.\nThe ladies of the Episcopal church\nentertained this afternoon for Mrs.\nJ. Fell, who is about to leave the\ncity. Monday afternoon the P. E.\nO.\u2019s entertained for Mrs. Fell.\nYesterday Justice of the Peace 1J.\nE. Crawford officiated at the mar\nriage of Frank Fleisliber and Katie\nHeble. The bride and groom are\nfrom\" the Bohemian neighborhbod\nnear Odell. Mr. Fleisliber is a far\nmer.\n\nHinshaw Better.\nCongressman Hinshaw returned to\nthis city Tuesday morning from Spar\ntansburg, S. C., where he left the\nLatimer funeral train on account of\nillness, says a Washington dispatch.\nHe seems to have almost entirely re\ncovered, and it is understood that his\nillness was of a temporary nature,\nbrought on by lack of exercise and\noverwork. Mr. Hinshaw his been\nvery busy since the beginning of the\nsession, and his duties have occupied\nhis time so fully that he has hot been\nable to take proper care of his\nRing's Little Liver Pills wake up\nlasy livers, clean the system and\nclear On skin. Try them for hU\ntousnesa and sick headache. Pnce\n26c. Sold by J. W. Busweil. 4\n00000000000000000*0\nO WEATHER FORECAST.\no For Beatrice and vicinity: o\no Fair and warmer tonight and o\no Friday. o\no O O O o o o.o ooooooooooo\nThe Eighth tirade.\nThe last few days have added a\nsufficient number to the list of appli\ncants for eighth grade examinations\nto make 'the total number nearly 350.\nOf this number, I fully expect 250 to\npass the examinations and become el\nigible to the free high school privi\nlege.\nThe size of this eighth grade class\nis constantly increasing, having\ngrown from 69 applicants in 1904 to\nthe present number.\u2014Anna V. Day,\ncounty superintendent\n1HE niUSIRMED\nliCIURE OH HER IR\nT-j\nDr. Swartz Entertained Large\nand Appreciative Audi- A\nence Last. Night.\nA fine targe audienee Wap in-at-*\ntendance last evening at the illustra\nted Ben Hur lecture by Dr. Swartz,\nwhich would probably be considered\nthe most interesting of any yet giv\nen. Many of the pictures were 'su\nperb and the lecture\u2014like others in\nthe course given by Dr. Swartz\u2014was\nin the nature of impressions received\nas an onlooker, or as a review of the'\nbook Ben Hur, with the magnificent\nviews to make it very vivid and real.\nThe old but ever new and fascinating\nstory of the guest of the three wise\nmen and the guiding star, over the\nfoothills of old Judea, were beauti\nfully shown in the introduction to ths\nfirst five chapters of Ben Hur.\nAmong the thrilling events of this\nstory, pictured, was the pretty roof\nscene where Ben >Hur\u2019s mother gave\nto him, as a youth of nineteen, in his\nhour of discouragement and grief,\nthe inspiring admonition to be a sol\ndier of Jehovah, and paid also such\na grand and beautiful tribute to the\n\u201chated Jew\u201d as represented in the\ncharacters of its noble prophets and\npatriarchs which make of this chap\nter, as Dr. Swartz thought, the finest\nthing in the\" whole story.\nJoppa Gate, Ben Hur as a galley\nslave, the chariot race, street scenes\nin Antioch and Jerusalem and the\nmost Important events in the life of\nChrist, in many of which Ben Hur\ncame in touching personal contact\nwith him, were among the events\ndescribed and illustrated.\nWith the closing scenes of Christ's\nsacrificial life, with the crown of\nthorns on his brow, \u201cJesus Lover of\nMy Soul\u201d was sung by the audience.\nOne of the finest things of the eve\nning was the singing of. \u201cThe Holy\nCity\u201d by Mrs. H. A. Miller, behind\nthe screen on which the subject was\nillustrated. Her beautiful voice and\nexpressive rendering of the theme\nwere very fine and Impressive.\nIn moving pictures there were\nsome very pretty blble scenes, fine\nviews of Niagara Falks, etc.,' with a\nfunny and life-like picture of two\nfrogs in a clawing match which Dr.\nSwartz thought would well represent\ntwo humans in a discussion of polit\nical questions.\nOne of the prettiest of these views\nwas that of a big flock of little tots\nIn their white night dresses, scram\nbling up a long, wide stairway to\ntheir beds, in an orphans\u2019 home. The\nmoral of this was that it was the gos\npel of Christ which provided comfor\ntable beds and home to these little\nchildren. Christ cares -for them.\nDr. Swartz, in announcing his lec\nture for this evening on the Fall,of\nBabylon, said it was of importance to\nhear the first fifteen minutes of it,\nand urged therefore that all be on\ntime.\nEXHIBIT, CUR\nIN BEATRICE\nBurlington Exhibit of Farm\nProducts Visited by Many\nFarmres.\n\nTO BE HERE THREE DATS\nCap In Charge of D. Clem De\u00bbTCf\u2014\nHas Been on Road Since Janu\nary a\u2014Excellent Display\nof Products.\nThe Burlington farm products car\nw hich arrived in-Beatrice last eve\nning, has been visited ..today by a\nlarge crowd of interested farmers\nand citizens of Beatrice.\nThe car occupies a side track west\nof the* Burlington station and is in\ncharge of D. Ciena Deav&r. and S, B.\nHoward, who enjoy showing off the\nproducts of the west and explaining\nthe homestead laws and irrigation\nprojects.\nThe c*r is divided into fourteen\nbooths and each booth contains ex\nhibits of crops grown by irrigation\nand dry farmiSg along the Burling\nton in western Nebraska, Kansas,\nColorado, Montana and Wyoming.\nThe exhibits are nicely arranged and\nshow off the oats, wheat, rye/ corn,\npotatoes \u201cand other products of that\nsection to the best advantage. An ex\nhibit of interest is the Macaroni\nwheat.\nThis car was sent out by the Bur\nlington in Nebraska January 2. It\nwill exhibit until', April 1. The pub\nlic in general is invited to call and\nthe men in charge will do their best\nto answer all questions.\nMr. Howard states that wherever\nthe car has exhibited, large crowds\nhave been in attendance and that it\nis proving to be an effective way of\nadvertising the Big Horn basin coun\ntry.\nRailroads Will Obey law.\nOmaha, Neb., Feb. 26.\u2014The three\nprincipal lines of railroads in Nebras\nka were represented at a meeting of\noperating and traffic officials held at\nthe office of General Manager Mohler,\nat which ft was decided to obey the\nnew nine hour law literally as well\nas to follow its spirit. There were\npresent at the meeting. General Man\nager'Mohler of the Union Pacific,\nHoldrege of the Burlington and Wal\nters of the Northwestern, and gen\neral superintendents and traffic offi-1\ncials of all three lines. Following the\nmeeting it was stated that about 150 j\nadditional operators would be need-1\ned and that the new-foads would be j\nready to start the new system Sun- i\nday morning, March 1. No stations j\nwill be closed as a result of the newi\nlaw, but a reduction of train service I\nis probable. All the traffic officials j\nagreed that the receipts for the past j\ntwo. months were far short ~bf the\nsame period last year and that aotion\nlooking to a ^responding redaction\nof expenditures would be necessary.\nBranches which formerly had two\ntrains daily will In many instances\nbe cut down to one and one train\nbranches will have to put up with a\ntrain three days'a week.\nUindernagle-Broslus.\nPhillip A'. Bindernagle, a promt\nnent young farmer of this vicinity,\nwas married yesterday afternoon at\n3 o\u2019clock in the Lutheran church at\nSunbury, Pa., to Miss Bertha A. Bro\nsius of that place. Rev. 1). N. Gear\nhardt officiating.\nMiss Brosius is a graduate of the\nL\nSunbury Commercial school and un\ntil recently held a position In one of\nthe leading mercantile establishments\nif Williamsport, Pa. The'groom is\na son of\" Mr. and Mrs. Phillip Blnder\nnagle, highly respected farmers who\nreside east of the city.\nAfter a honeymoon tour in the\neast Mr. Bindernagle will return with\nhis bride and make his home on his\nfarm in this vicinity.\nMrs. C. 8. Bradley Entertains.\nThe Fortnightly club was enter\ntained yesterday afternoon by Mrs.\nC. S. Bradley.\ni The subject considered was an un\nusually interesting one, .\u201cFamous\nMusical Organizations in America,\u201d\n\u201cThfe Thomas Orchestra,\u201d \u201cThe\nBoston Symphony,\u201d and \u201cThe Marine\nBand.\u201d The first two papers were\nprepared by Mrs. Burch. She gave\na sketch of the life and work of The\nodore Thomas, the pioneer in orches\ntral organization and leadership. She\nalso gave a sketch of the Boston\nSymphony, one of the finest orches\ntras in the United States, established\nby Henry L. Higgenson.\nMrs. Pease spoke briefly of \"The\nMarine Band,\u201d tracing its growth\nfrom the early \u201cfife and drum corps\u201d\nto its present organization. She\nspoke of it as our national band and\nmentioned the Important part it plays\nin official government functions.\nAfter the program, the hostess\nserved refreshments and an hour was\nspent in sociability.\nThe club will meet next Wednes\nday with Mrs. Fisher!\nY. M. C. A. Notes.\nThe lecture on the Fall of Babylon\nis considered one of Dr. Swartz\u2019 mas\nterpieces. Those who enjoyed the\nlecture Sunday night will not want\nto miss this one. Dr. Swartz is mak\ning a \u201chit\u201d in the city.\nMrs. Henry Miller, who sang the\n\u201cHoly City\u201d at the Swartz lecture\nlast-night, will sing the \u201cNinety and\nNine\u201d tonight. Miss Mabel Firoved\nwill acompany her.\nThe shuffle board which was pre\nsented to the Y. M. C. A. by the Crab\ntree Forensic club, has been placed\nin the lot^by and is proving popular\nwith the members. The last shuf\nfle board that was in the city was\nused in a Court street saloon eighteen\nor twenty years ago.\nThe Y. M. C. A. members will tie\nsorry to lose Mr. Charles English\nwho has been physical director for*\nthe last six weeks, and Who now ac\ncepts the entire charge of the Exeter\nassociation. Mr. English has the\nmaking of a leader in the Y. M. C. A.\nwork and the Beatrice boys will not\nforget him.j A large senior class is\ndesired tonight. Mr. English will\nleave Sunday.\nThe Y. M. C. A, is glad to learn\nthat a free base ball^ park is to be\nopened this summer. ^It is the plan\nof the members to have a boat'house\nup the river, as boating will be part\nof the association work in the phys\nical department. This park will be\nconvenient for the members.\nAssessors to Meet in Lincoln.\nSecretary George D. Bennett of the\nstate board of equalization and as\nsessment has called a meeting of\ncounty assessors to be held at the\nstate house Saturday, March 10, at 1\np. m. Since the adoption of the coun\nty assessor law it has been customary\nto hold meetings for the purpose of\ndiscussing the work of assessing prop\nerty. This year for the first time in\nfour years real estate is to be reas\nsessed. In addition to this work the\nlast legislature imposed upon asses\nsors new duties in assessing railroad\nproperty for local assessment. This\nwork is to be done under the law\nknown as the terminal tax law. Oth\ner changes, mostly relating to the as\nsessment of real estate, were made\nby the last legislature and it is be\nlieved best for the county assessors\nto get together and discuss their du\nties. Secretary Bennett has arranged\nto have the state board of assess\nment and equalization attend the\nmeeting. This hoard comprises Gov\nernor Sheldon, treasurer Brian, Land\nCommissioner Eaton, Auditor Searle j\nand Secretary of State Junkin.\u2014Lin-j\ncoin Journal. I\nEntertain Nebraska Educators.\nWashington, D. C., Feb. 26.\u2014The\nsenators and members of the Nebras\nka delegation are vieing with each\nother in an effort to show the Ne\nbraska educators who are in Wash\nington attending the national confer\nence of superintendents a pleasant\ntime while* here. Early this morn\ning Congressman Boyd took the dele\ngation through the state, war \u25a0and\ntreasury departments. At the war\ndepartment they were introduced to\nthe .big rotund secretary who gave\nthem a hearty greeting. The party\nwent to the capitol shortly before the\nsession opened, and were presented\nto Speaker Cannon by Judge Boyd\nand Congressman Pollard.\n''James H. Hazelton of Filley, and\nMiss Gussie V. Smith of Swanton,\nNeb., were married in county court\nthis morning, Judge H. E. Spafford\n\u2018officiating.\nMr. Hazelton is the son of George\nis a young farmer. His bride is the\ndaughter \"of Mr. and Mrs. David\nSmith, former residents of Filley,\nwho now reside in Swanton. Mr. and\nMrs. Hazelton will make their bourn\nin Denver. v\niS\nMarried.\nHazelton, a resident\n-V i*\nDecided to Move Their Meet\ning Point Farther West\nfor Next Tear.\n\u25a0mi:\nTH\u00a3 AUTOMOBILE SHOW\nState Meeting of Opticians\u2014Lincoln\nDoctor Complains of Discrimi\nnation\u2014Stockman\nKicks.\n\nf\nLincoln, Feb. 27.\u2014The thfrty\nsixth annual meeting of the State\nPress association closed last evening,\nthe editors being the guests of Lin\ncoln Typographical Union at h ball\ngiven'in celebration of the twenty\nfifth anniversary of the union's\nfounding. The grand march waa led\nby Governor Sheldon and Mrs. Shel\ndon. On behalf of ^he State Press\nassociation, F. L. Martini presented\nthe union with a handsome silver,\nwater service.\nAt yesterday\u2019s session L. A. Var\nner of the Sterling Sun, was elected\npresident of the association; W. G\nJohns of the Wood River Sunbeam,\nsecretary-treasurer; N. J. Ludi of\nthe Wahoo Democrat, vice president\nand Mrs. W. A. Keithley of the\nSyracuse Journal, corresponding sec\nretary.\nGrand Island was selected as the\nplace of holding the 1909 meeting.\nThe resolutions committee through\nthe chairman, Ross Hammond, called\non the association members to intro\nduce better methods into the conduct\nof their business, declared that the\nprofession would attempt to reach a\nhigher plaiie of Ideals and standards\nin order to perform its duty to the\nwoi\u2019M more effectively. He urged all\neditors within the state to send cop\nles of their papers to the state his\ntorical society, and wound up with\nthis frown on the late ruling of the\npostofllce department;\n'\u201cResolved, That we recognise to\u2019\nthe recent1 rulings of the postofllce\ndepartment concerning limitations of\nunpaid newspaper subscriptions to\nthe right of second class rates of post\nage as a stimulus to the adoption of\nmore businesslike methods by pub\nlishers; but we submit that the on-\nforcement of this ruling threatens\nthe country publisher\u2019s right of im\nplied contract and is governmental\ninterference with the legitimate busi\nness relations between the country\npublisher and his patrons.,\nx The automobilevshow at Ttow Audi\ntorium is attracting people from aft\never the state. Forty cars of every'\ndescription are on exhibition. Throe\nNebraska-made machines are on ex\nhibition.\nDr. Martin ana ur. isvans or w\nlumbus, employed as surgeons by\nthe Union Pacific railroad, were Wed\nnesday taken Into court and bound\nover for appearance in the district\ncourt for accepting a pass from the\nrailroad. The prosecution was Insti\ntuted by County Attorney Hensley,\nassisted by Judge J. J. Sullivan. The\nlatter was authorized by Attorney\nGeneral Thompson to assist the coun\nty attorney. The doctors will have a\nhearing week after next.\nOver two hundred opticians attend\ned the state meeting ivhich closed\nlast evening. Officers for the ensulns\nyear were elected, standing commit\ntees were chosen and a movement\nlooking toward the establishment of\na permanent circulating library for\nopticians was adopted.\nDr. 'S. B. Hollenbeck of Lincoln has\ncomplained before the state railway\ncommission that an extra charge of j\n$2 a month is made for a residence\ntelephone in his home, the company\ncharging him $4 a month, while ordi\nnary patrons are charged $2 for the\nsame time. He declares -this to be\ndiscrimination. The company ex\nplains this is done because in the di\nrectory the title \u201cDr.\u201d is prefixed to\nthe name and the advertisement is\nalleged to be worth the money.\nP. M. Frease, a stockman of North\nBend, has written the railroad com-\nmission that the man who calls the\ntrains in the Omaha Union station\n\u201c\u25a0bellows like a bull.\" He declares r\nno one can understand him and then\nhe continues that if information is\nasked of him on the side the chance\nis it may be wrong. He declares ho\nwas misinformed about the time of\ndeparture of a Union Pacific train\nand, supposing it to be thirty minutes\nlate, returned to find it departed on\ntime. Mr. Frease also wants to know\nif the commission cannot enforce s\nregulation that a freight caboose\nshall be stopped near, the depot In-\nstead of half a mile away.\n_____________ v\nThe Club\u2019s Resolutions.\nEditor of the Express: I notice in\nyour issue of last evening that the\ndirectors of the commercial club have\npassed a resolution pledging them\nselves to Work for the infliction of a\nheavy bonded indebtedness upon this\ncity. As a member of the club and\nafter consulting with other members,\n1 think I can safely say that such ac\ntion does not meet with the approval\nj of a majority of the enrolled mem-\nbers of the club.\u2014A. L. Green.","height":"27288","width":"20036"}}
